ch refers to the change in tones under the influence of adjacent words. The same Chinese character usually has different tones when it is pronounced in isolation, in words, and when it is put into a longer sentence. Tone sandhi is an important feature in Southern Min that’s not present in Mandarin. The rules for tone sandhi are EXTREMELY complicated and is almost impossible to be mastered by non-native speakers. (if you are interested, the second link below is a 200-page dissertation describing the tone sandhi in Southern Min in detail). Just knowing the tones for each Chinese character isn’t enough because you still have to learn how the tones change when they are combined with other words with different tones. That probably explains why the tones in Southern Min can be very challenging to learn. Hope you find this helpful.%0a%3c %0a%3c Citation %0a%3c Liu, Liquan, and René Kager. "Perception of tones by infants learning a non-tone language." Cognition 133.2 (2014): 385-394.%0a%3c %0a%3c Chen, Mao-Hsu. "Tone Sandhi Phenomena In Taiwan Southern Min." (2018).%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
